INSERT INTO djfk_course VALUES("19","2","Self Awareness","","img18.jpg","||/~Objective/~<p>By the end of this session you will be able to:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Understand the meaning of self-awareness in relation to coping with the challenges girls face, especially those related to employability.</li>\n<li>Know the 5 dimensions of an individual.</li>\n<li>Appreciate how the various dimensions affect a girl during puberty.</li>\n<li>Apply the understanding in everyday life.</li>\n</ol>/~Yes||/~Introduction/~<p>In order to cope with life challenges, develop healthy social relationships, make effective decisions and release our potential in life, a clear understanding of who we are is critical. We cannot understand other people if we do not understand ourselves and neither can we know what we are good at if we do not understand ourselves well.</p>/~Yes||/~Activity 1 a: Who are you? (3 minutes)/~<p>In this activity you are required to take a piece of paper and write about who are.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~Activity 1 b: Who are you? (3 minutes)/~<p>Repeat previous activity by writing about who are without using your name, age, class or where you stay.</p>\n<p>Looking deeply into who we are is that there are discoveries that we make when we do so. The dimensions of an individual exercise help us realize that.</p>/~Yes||/~Diagram on Dimensions of an Individual/~<p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" alt=\"\" width=\"320\" height=\"292\" /></p>\n<p>To understand oneself there are five dimensions namely emotional, physical, mental, spiritual and social.</p>\n<p>This helps appreciate abilities including talents and skills set, feelings, strengths, and weaknesses. At the same time there is a need to accept those aspects that one cannot change e.g. color of skin, height, tribe etc. Failure to accept what one cannot change will lead to low self-esteem and this will have negative impact in one&rsquo;s life.</p>\n<p>Let&rsquo;s explore possible areas of similarity</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"600\" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Physical</strong>: height, weight, skin colour, hair</li>\n<li><strong>Social</strong>: talk to new people, quiet and withdrawn,</li>\n<li><strong>Emotional</strong>: Happy, bored, sad, anxious, worry, fear, embarrassed, etc.</li>\n<li><strong>Mental</strong>: Visual, artistic, talents, gifts, logical thinkers, story tellers, etc.</li>\n<li><strong>Spiritual</strong>: Belief in the supernatural.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The different aspects of who we are many times affect each other.&nbsp; For example, when you are sick, you become emotionally low and you are likely to stay on your own and avoid people, be mentally disturbed and seek spiritual intervention.&nbsp; Is it possible that, like wise, when we are going through menstruation, a physical aspect, we can get emotionally affected, mentally disturbed especially if we are not well prepared and may not want to interact with people?&nbsp; Does it happen?&nbsp; It is very helpful then, to know ourselves and how we are affected during these times?</p>/~Yes||/~Activity/~<p><strong>Imagine</strong> that someone wants to send a letter to them in school. But instead of writing the name on the envelope, the sender will write the description of the person. What description would they give so that it is obvious that the letter is to them and not anyone else imagining that there will be several of those letters coming to different people?</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Write</strong> the letter using the following dimensions of an individual;</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Their physical appearance in terms of: height, shape, complexion and any other thing they would like the well-wisher to know about the way they look.</li>\n<li>The things they are good at and what they are yet to develop.</li>\n<li>Emotions they often experience (those they regard as helpful and those that are negative).</li>\n<li>At least five spiritual values and believes that influence the way they live.</li>\n<li>Three gifting/talents or special abilities they have.</li>\n<li>The kind of people they usually socialize with.</li>\n<li>Three major weaknesses that they have.</li>\n<li>Two social activities you engage in.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>We are all different and these differences are the ones that make us unique.</p>\n<p><strong>Self-awareness</strong> <strong>Fruit Tree</strong>:</p>\n<p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" alt=\"\" width=\"386\" height=\"443\" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Roots represent our values; background (family; social; schooling)</li>\n<li>Stem represents: attitudes (towards self; others; community; work) or thought system</li>\n<li>Fruits represent: Our behavior; mannerisms</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~Activity/~<p>&nbsp;How are the three areas of the self-awareness fruit tree related?</p>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz/~/~Yes","","","","",""),
("20","3","Body Changes at Puberty","","img12.jpg","||/~Objectives/~<p>The objectives of this module are to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Increase your knowledge about physical, emotional, and sexual development associated with puberty.</li>\n<li>Increase your sense of self-control for sexual abstinence</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~Puberty/~<p>Puberty is a period of transition, you are no longer a child, but not yet an adult. All the changes that take place in your body during puberty are caused by hormones.</p>\n<p>Hormones are chemical products that are produced in all kind of places in your body. They move around in your body through your blood, from the place where they are produced to the place where they have to do their work.</p>\n<p>Girls generally begin puberty earlier than boys. Puberty can begin as early as age 9 or as late as age 16 and it is completely normal whichever age it starts.</p>\n<p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" alt=\"\" width=\"544\" height=\"334\" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~During puberty/~<p>During puberty it is not only your body that changes.</p>\n<p>During puberty:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>These sex hormones then inform the ovaries of girls to release an egg.</li>\n<li>The brain starts to make a special type of hormones which send messages to the genitals, to start producing sex hormones.</li>\n<li>The sex hormones are also responsible for the changes in your body and the changes of your feelings and moods.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>All of these changes that your bodies are undergoing can also affect how you feel from one minute to the next. Perhaps one minute you are laughing about a funny story and then the next minute you are sad.</p>/~Yes||/~Activity/~/~Yes||/~Puberty Summary/~<p>All these changes that we experience during puberty are completely normal. However, they happen at different times for different people. It does not matter if your body starts early or late with changing. It can be annoying though if you are the first one or the last one in your class or group whose body starts changing, because young people like to tease each other with the changes that are happening. Knowing that these changes are normal and that each person takes his/her own time to go through these changes will help you gain more confidence in your body.</p>\n<p>During puberty there is a lot of worrying about friends. It is possible that some of your friends get interested in the opposite sex, while you have no interest whatsoever in such things. You may feel an outsider, or jealous, and that is also normal. Many friendships survive puberty but there are also friendships that dilute.</p>\n<p>As you can see there are many changes that young people experience as they prepare to become an adult. It is important that you know your body and take good care of it. Part of learning about your body is to understand some of the unique changes that girls experience in becoming women.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" alt=\"\" width=\"781\" height=\"490\" /></p>\n<p><strong>Female</strong>:</p>\n<p>External genitals: vagina, clitoris, inner lips, outer lips</p>\n<p>Internal genitals: ovaries or egg stores, womb, egg tubes, opening of the womb, vagina</p>\n<p>Let&rsquo;s look at each of these parts in more detail. We will start with the external female genitals.</p>/~Yes||/~External Female Genitals/~<p>These are difficult to see because they are between the legs.</p>\n<p>They include:</p>\n<p>Inner lips, outer lips and clitoris; the outer lips protect the vaginal opening. The inner lips and the clitoris are sensitive. If you could look inside the body of a girl, you would see the vagina, cervix, womb, two fallopian tubes and two ovaries.</p>\n<p><strong>Vagina</strong>: it is a tube of approximately 20 cm long, with an elastic lining of soft skin. The opening of the vagina is bigger than the opening for urine. It is the corridor between the womb and the outside of the body.</p>\n<p><strong>Ovaries</strong>: they are 2 and both ovaries are the size of a passion fruit. The eggs are already there from birth, but they only start to ripen during puberty.</p>\n<p><strong>Fallopian or egg tubes</strong>: they are the tubes through which the egg travels to the womb.</p>\n<p><strong>Womb or uterus:</strong> is a strong hollow muscle that is connected to the egg tubes and the vagina. This is the place where the baby develops (it is the size of an upside down pear).</p>\n<p><strong>Cervix</strong>: is the part of the uterus that connects to the vagina. During pregnancy it stays closed to protect the developing baby (fetus).</p>/~Yes||/~Jacky\'s Story/~<h3>Background</h3>\n<p>Jacky, Mercy&rsquo;s younger sister wakes up one morning to find her underwear and nightdress stained with blood. She is worried that she may be sick. Just as she gets a &lsquo;kanga&rsquo; to tie around her waist to hide the stain, Mercy walks into the room</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Good morning Jacky</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jacky</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Morning sister (fumbling with the &lsquo;kanga&rsquo;). I think I am unwell. I woke up and my nightdress was stained with blood</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>There is nothing wrong with you. Congratulations you have just started your first menstrual period and you are now a young woman who is capable of getting pregnant and having a baby</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jacky</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Is this normal, won&rsquo;t I lose too much blood and become weak?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Yes it is very normal. I also started having my periods at about your age and it will not make you become sick or weak.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jacky</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Mercy I will not leave this room today because my clothes will get stained and everyone will laugh at me.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Having a period is nothing to be embarrassed about. However, you will have to use pads to absorb the blood and to protect your clothes from getting stained.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jacky</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Yes, but what will happen if I start my period in church or at the market place?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Your periods will come approximately once a month. It&rsquo;s good to prepare yourself by carrying your pad for protection when it starts. There are two kinds of pads that you can use. You can use pads made out of rags, and these can be washed every time they get soiled, or you can use disposable ones, which need to be dropped in a pit latrine and dustbin after use. It is also important that you take good care of your body. You should wash yourself every day with water and soap.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jacky</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Mercy Does this mean that I am now a grown woman?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Well, you are certainly on your way to becoming one. You are capable of getting pregnant if you have sex.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jacky</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>I am not ready for motherhood yet and I want to be like you Mercy. I want to wait until I finish my studies and reach my goal of becoming a nurse in future.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>That is good my sister, the healthy choice to make is to take good care of yourself in order to achieve your goal. I have decided to abstain from sex and you can do the same to prevent getting HIV, STIs and unwanted pregnancy.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jacky</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>I will abstain from sex until am ready and thanks sis for explaining this to me.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>/~Yes||/~During puberty II/~<p>During puberty, hormones are produced that trigger the ovaries to start releasing one egg every month. The egg will travel from the ovary to the womb through the fallopian tube. Every month the womb (uterus) prepares itself for a possible pregnancy. The lining (or the wall) of the womb thickens for the preparation of a baby in case of pregnancy. If the girl doesn&rsquo;t get pregnant, the thickening leaves the body through the vagina as blood. This is called &ldquo;menstruation&rdquo; or &ldquo;having a period&rdquo;. Periods will come approximately once every month.</p>\n<p>Sometimes these changes cause a lot of concern and worry among young people. Understanding that these changes are normal will help us make healthy choices about our life.</p>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz/~/~Yes","","","","",""),
("21","4","Sexuality","","img16.jpg","||/~Objectives/~<ul>\n<li>Increase participants&rsquo; knowledge about HIV/ AIDS and HIV risk-associated behavior.</li>\n<li>Help participants identify behaviors that place people at risk for contracting sexually transmitted infections, including HIV.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You are now going to read a story about HIV. This story will help you understand the facts about HIV. To do this, you are going to read the Mercy Story.</p>/~Yes||/~HIV Talk/~<p>It&rsquo;s mid-morning on Tuesday and Mercy and her friend Jane are walking home from the lake where they have been washing clothes. Jane reminds Mercy that a team of youth counselors from a local youth center will be giving a talk on HIV later that afternoon at the social hall....</p>\n<table width=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>Oh! Today is Tuesday; remember the local community health worker announced there would be a talk on AIDS today afternoon at the social hall?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>I have always wanted to know more about AIDS; there is so much conflicting information about it.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>I know that HIV is transmitted through sex but I don&rsquo;t understand exactly how it&rsquo;s transmitted.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>Maybe you are right, because our neighbor Mr. Ochien&rsquo;g died of AIDS but the wife looks healthy and I overheard my mother saying that she tested positive for HIV.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>(looking confused) So does it mean you can be HIV positive and yet you look healthy and live a normal life?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>I don&rsquo;t understand how that happens, but I have heard that sometimes a baby can get it from the mother and live up to an adult.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>So Mercy, can young people like us get HIV?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>If babies can get it then I think we are also at risk.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>But I think that can only happen if you have sex with an infected person.</p>\n<p>but how can I know if he is infected just by looking?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>(As they approach Jane&rsquo;s compound)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>There is really a lot I want to know and I can&rsquo;t wait for that talk. I want to know how I can protect myself from getting HIV. I hope you will pick me up so we can attend the talk.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"594\">\n<p>Yes, my friend I will pick you up in the afternoon.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~Knowing HIV/~<h4>What is HIV?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>HIV, Human Immunodeficiency Virus, is the virus that causes AIDS. HIV passes from person to person through blood and sexual contact.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>What is AIDS?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>AIDS, Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome, is caused by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV). On average, it takes about 10 years to develop AIDS after infection with HIV.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>How are HIV and AIDS different?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>HIV is the virus which infects the body. It weakens the immune system. AIDS is the disease that results from damage to the immune system. With AIDS, the body is unable to fight off infections, which lead to many rare, life-threatening diseases.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>What is the immune system?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The immune system is a collection of white blood cells and chemicals that act as the body&rsquo;s defense against disease agents and other things that can make people sick</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>What behaviors put people at risk for HIV infection?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Sexual behaviors with an infected person, Sharing needles, razors or any sharp objects with an infected person,</li>\n<li>From an HIV infected mother to baby (either during pregnancy, at birth or through breast feeding) Blood transfusion with blood of an infected person</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Through what 4 body fluids is HIV known to be transmitted?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Blood, semen, vaginal secretions, and breast milk</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>How is HIV not transmitted?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Mosquitoes, shaking hands, sharing eating utensils, living in the same house with someone who has HIV.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>How can you best prevent HIV?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Practicing abstinence (avoiding any sexual activity that involves contact with blood, semen, and vaginal secretions), is the 100% effective way to avoid HIV.</li>\n<li>Never sharing needles, razors or other sharp objects of any kind.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Who can get HIV?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Anyone can get HIV. Anybody who gets in contact with blood, semen or vaginal fluids &amp; breast milk from a person who is HIV infected can get HIV</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>How can you know if you have HIV?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A person may look very healthy and not even know that he/she has the HIV virus. The only way to know is to go for an HIV-test. You can learn your HIV-status at a VCT center. Early symptoms of AIDS may include severe or prolonged fever, swollen lymph glands, lingering fatigue and persistent night sweats.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In the later stages of AIDS, people have trouble with movement, memory, diarrhea, unintentional weight loss, and general weakness.</p>/~Yes||/~What is VCT?/~<p>VCT stands for Voluntary Counseling and Testing. VCT services provide a convenient way to learn your HIV status. If you decide to go for CT, you will meet a counselor who will talk to you in a private and confidential place.</p>\n<p>Before the test, the counselor will ask you some questions to assess your readiness for the test and prepare you for the results. The test itself takes about 15 minutes. After the test, you will also receive post-test counseling to help you deal with the test results. It is a convenient way to learn your HIV status.</p>\n<p>Knowing your HIV status is beneficial for many reasons:</p>\n<p>Those who test negative can access to information that can help them to maintain behavior to prevent acquisition of HIV</p>\n<p>Those who test positive can learn how to live longer, healthier lives and prevent transmission to others. They can also gain early access to HIV- specific care, treatment and support as well as referrals for other health services. Knowing your status also helps you to plan for the future.</p>/~Yes||/~ Is there a cure for AIDS?/~<p>There is no cure for AIDS. However, there are now drugs available that help you live longer and better. These drugs are called anti-retroviral drugs. But you will have to take the drugs every day for the rest of your life. It is much better to prevent HIV infection by practicing sexual abstinence.</p>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz I/~/~Yes||/~Do you have stigma?/~<p><strong>The Nancy Story</strong></p>\n<p>Mercy and Jane are coming back from the HIV talk. They are discussing that during the talk, Nancy, a 15 year-old girl who is Mercy&rsquo;s classmate gave a moving testimony on how she got HIV. Nancy is the lead singer in Mercy&rsquo;s class in their days in Primary School.</p>\n<p>Mercy and Jane are deeply moved by Nancy&rsquo;s story and it is the focus of their discussion on their way home.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>I still find it hard to believe that Nancy is HIV positive</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>I am also shocked, Nancy is only 14, and I didn&rsquo;t think it was possible for such a young person to get HIV!</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>And all this time she has been such an energetic netball player above you are mentioning that she is the lead singer in her your class in the school, she looked so strong and full of life. I wonder if she will still be able to achieve her dream of playing in the national netball team.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>I doubt if she will be able to. But I didn&rsquo;t hear clearly, whom did she say she got it from?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>No Jane, she didn&rsquo;t say the name of the person. She just said an older man who worked at the local post office lured her into having sex. She said the man convinced her by promising to buy her all nice things she would ever want. Little did she know that the man was infected with HIV!</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>How did she find out that she is HIV positive because according to me, she still looks healthy and it&rsquo;s hard to believe she is infected?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>She must have gone for VCT at the youth center. Remember the youth counselors said they provide VCT services to young people like us at the youth center.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>&nbsp;I am truly moved by that story my friend. I noticed tears streaming down her face as she was explaining that we should be careful to avoid getting HIV.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Yes, she said we should abstain from sex. She also emphasized the importance of knowing your HIV status.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Ruth</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>Jane, I suggest we go to the VCT center to know our HIV status.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"59\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"578\">\n<p>What do you think?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz II/~/~Yes||/~The Nancy Story II/~<p>You have learned a lot from the story. You have seen how Nancy was promised many nice things. As a result of these promises she gave in to sex and she acquired HIV. HIV infection can happen to anyone who engages in risky behavior; even young people like you can get HIV through sexual intercourse. It is important to note that when you have sex with someone who is HIV positive you are at risk of getting STIs including HIV or getting pregnant. The best choice to make is to abstain from sex.</p>/~Yes||/~Voluntary Testing for HIV/~<p>The only way to be sure whether you have HIV or not is to go for testing at a VCT. As we said earlier, VCT stands for Voluntary Counseling and Testing.</p>\n<p>If you decide to go for VCT, you will meet a counselor who will talk to you in a private and confidential place. The counselor will ask you some questions about your risk/sexual behavior and will assess your readiness for the test and its results, either a HIV-positive result or a HIV-negative result. The test itself takes about 15 minutes. After the test, you will also receive post-test counseling to help you deal with the test results. At the youth center, you will find youth counselors who will help you in a youth friendly way. You will feel comfortable to get the services.</p>\n<p>Why is it important for a teen to learn his/her HIV status?</p>\n<p>HIV has no cure. However, there are drugs that can help you live longer if you have HIV. Learning your status can help you plan better how to stay healthy if you have the virus. If you do not have the virus, you will also be able to plan better how to be safe.</p>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz III/~/~Yes","","","","",""),
("23","5","Teen Pregnancy and Sexually Transmitted Infections","","eye-for-ebony-399310-unsplash.jpg","||/~Objectives/~<p>The Objectives of this module are to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Increase your knowledge about sexually transmitted infections.</li>\n<li>Increase your perceived vulnerability to STIs and pregnancy.</li>\n<li>Increase your understanding of the consequences of teen pregnancy.</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~What is STI?/~<p>We just discussed a lot about HIV. We will now talk about other infections that we can get by engaging in sex. The infections I am referring to are Sexually Transmitted Infections.</p>\n<p>Sexually transmitted infections (STIs) can be passed on when you have unprotected sex or close sexual contact with someone who already has an STI.</p>\n<p>The following is a list of common STIs:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Chlamydia,</li>\n<li>gonorrhea,</li>\n<li>syphilis,</li>\n<li>genital herpes,</li>\n<li>HIV and trichomoniasis.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>What are the signs and symptoms of STIs?</p>\n<p>There are many symptoms caused by STIs these include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sores, blisters, warts or pimples near the Genital area or mouth</li>\n<li>Unusual discharge (in color, texture, Amount or odor) from vagina.</li>\n<li>Pain or itching in the pubic/genital area.</li>\n<li>Burning when urinating.</li>\n<li>Pain in the abdominal area (in women).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Having any of these symptoms doesn&rsquo;t necessarily mean that one has an STI; they could be symptoms of other diseases.</p>\n<p>However if a person has had sex and presents any of these symptoms it is very important that he or she go to the health provider for a checkup. Make sure to insist on abstinence.</p>\n<p>Present with different signs and symptoms. If you have any of these signs and symptoms, don&rsquo;t ignore them and seek advice from your health provider. It is also important to note that a person who has an STI may not have any symptoms. The person may not even know that he or she has an STI.</p>\n<p>Consequences of untreated STIs</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Embarrassment</li>\n<li>Baby born with STI or hurt by STI</li>\n<li>Chronic pelvic pain (Gonorrhea and Chlamydia)</li>\n<li>Cervical cancer (Genital Warts)</li>\n<li>Pregnancy outside the womb (Chlamydia)</li>\n<li>Blindness (Syphilis-if left untreated)</li>\n<li>Paralysis (Syphilis- if left untreated)</li>\n<li>Not being able to have children (if Pelvic Inflammatory Disease (PID) is not treated, the tubes may close and make one unable to have children); also men can get infertile!&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>STIs increase the chance of HIV infection. STIs cause a disruption of the normal lining of the genital organs. When one has an STI, one is more likely to get infected by the HIV virus during sex because the HIV virus can enter the body through these lesions and infect the person with HIV.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>STI s hurt women more than men. If a woman has sex with an infected man, she is twice as likely to get an STI as if a man has sex with an infected woman. Women are less likely than men to notice symptoms if they have certain STI. Therefore; a woman is less likely to know that she has an STI. Women also suffer more consequences than men. This includes: cervical cancer, chronic pelvic pain and transmission of STI to her baby.</p>\n<p>Not all STIs are curable. For example HIV and genital herpes are not curable.</p>\n<p>If a person is concerned about having an STI, it is very important that he/she goes to the health provider and gets a checkup. There is no need to be ashamed to seek help. Know that you are doing the right thing by seeking treatment. Remember that the doctor will maintain confidentiality and will not tell others about your condition.</p>\n<p>You now know the basic information that will allow you to avoid getting an STI. Remember how STIs are transmitted, some of the signs and symptoms, how to avoid STIs and what to do if you suspect that you have an STI. Part of acting responsibly and making healthy choices is being informed. You are now informed about STIs so be responsible and abstain to prevent getting STIs.</p>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz I/~/~Yes||/~Review /~<p>One person can infect many people by passing the disease-causing germs e.g. viruses to someone who passes it on to the next person</p>\n<ul>\n<li>STIs can be spread through sexual intercourse.</li>\n<li>It doesn&rsquo;t feel good to have an STI</li>\n<li>Abstinence can prevent STI transmission.</li>\n<li>You can&rsquo;t tell by just looking at someone who is infected and who isn&rsquo;t 13.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Let&rsquo;s reflect again about the question, &ldquo;Who can get an STI?&rdquo; we have learned that STIs are a threat to us all.</p>\n<p>STI s among adolescents is real. It&rsquo;s important that you understand that if you have sex, you are putting yourself at risk for infection.</p>\n<p>The more you know about STIs, the better prepared you are to protect yourself from infection</p>\n<p>Protecting yourself from infection is your responsibility. Only you can choose to abstain from sex you can choose to prevent your risk of getting STI. And this is a healthy choice for a brighter future.</p>/~Yes||/~Teenage Pregnancy/~<p>We are now going to talk about adolescent pregnancy. We are going to read a story about Mercy and her friends</p>\n<p><strong><br /> Jennifer&rsquo;s Story</strong></p>\n<p>Jennifer is a 14-year-old girl who will sit for her KCPE exams with Mercy this year. She cheated to have sex for the first time with her boyfriend, Odhiambo who is 15 years old refused to abstain from sex. After missing her periods thrice, she went for a test at the local youth friendly health center. Unfortunately she found out that she is pregnant. She has been trying to hide it from everybody but today after church she meets Mercy and her other friends who ask her why she has been keeping to herself lately. She decides to tell her friends what has happened to her...</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table width=\"662\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Mercy:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>Hey there is Jennifer. I wonder if everything is OK with her. We have not seen her for a while.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Oscar:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>Ah! I am not surprised, you girls sometimes like keeping to yourself.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Jane:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>Stop talking like that Oscar, you never know she could be having a problem. Let&rsquo;s hurry and talk to her.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>(They all rush to reach Jennifer)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Mercy:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>(To Jennifer) hi my friend, is everything okay? You seem to be so withdrawn these days!</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Jennifer:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>Actually I have something to tell you, I am 5 months pregnant.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>Odhiambo persuaded me to have sex and even though it was the first time, I got pregnant. I have been trying to keep to myself because I am afraid what my mother will do when she finds out.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>(Jane starts shifting around uncomfortably)</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Jane:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>I&rsquo;m also suspecting that I could be pregnant. I have been dating with Hillary, last week we went to the disco matanga at the funeral at Mzee Olado&rsquo;s home. I have not had my period since then and I&rsquo;m wondering what happened or if I could be pregnant.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Jennifer:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>Oh no! Not you too. The way you are talking, you are definitely pregnant.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Mercy:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>And what will happen to you now?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Jennifer:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>I can stay in school for the time being until I deliver... I wonder what will happen to my plans to go and study fashion design. My parents are very disappointed and ashamed of me. Odhiambo denies any responsibility and wants nothing to do with me.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Mercy:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>I feel so sorry for both of you. However, Jane you should visit the health centre for a pregnancy test. I heard that sometimes a girl might miss her periods, but that doesn&rsquo;t necessarily mean that she is pregnant.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Jane:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>Will you come with me to the health centre Mercy?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Mercy:</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>Yes my friend, we can go in the evening</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>After school, Mercy and Oscar accompany Jane and Hillary to a youth friendly health centre. They wait outside as Jane goes in for the test.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Hillary</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>&nbsp;I&rsquo;m so terrified; I don&rsquo;t know what results Jane is going to come out with from the test. If she is pregnant I would not even be able...</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>&nbsp;(excitedly) I&rsquo;m not pregnant. The test was negative I will not risk again. I will not engage in risky activities.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"73\">\n<p>Hillary</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"589\">\n<p>&nbsp;I&rsquo;m so relieved; I don&rsquo;t know what I would have done. However this was a lesson to me, from now we are not going to go out at night. I really like Jane and would not like her to blame me for messing up her life. She wanted me to abstain, but I convinced her because all my friends seem to be having sex and they were pressuring me to do the same. Now I know the risk of having sex as a teen.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table width=\"662\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>&nbsp;I also have myself to blame; I should have been more firm in my resolve not to have sex.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>&nbsp;I plead with you my friends, practice abstinence always because if you don&rsquo;t, you risk getting pregnant, getting an STI including HIV. This might stop you from reaching your future goals.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Oscar</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>Let us all make a pact to abstain. We will all support each other in doing this.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>Yes, let&rsquo;s do that. Others should not influence us into engaging in unsafe behavior. We should always keep our focus on our future goals.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>I hope to become a respected teacher and I will abstain from sex so that I can achieve my goals.</p>\n<p>They all thank the clinician and bid her goodbye and leave. It&rsquo;s now getting rather late and they all hurry home.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>Seven months later Jennifer had her baby. Mercy, Jane and Oscar go to visit her</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>&nbsp;Hi Jennifer, how are you? How is the baby?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Jennifer</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>I am fine and so is the baby but he is asleep now. How are you doing? And how about the plans you had for joining High school?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Oscar</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>&nbsp;(Happily) we are fine. Mercy is already at Mama Ngina Girls and she just came back for mid-term break.</p>\n<p>My father has also registered me for a carpentry course at the youth polytechnic.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Jennifer</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>(sadly) I wish I could turn back the clock. Life is so difficult for me.</p>\n<p>I was in labor for 16 hours and because my body was not fully developed, it was all so painful, and finally they had to operate on me to save the baby who would have died otherwise. After my parents paid the hospital bill they said that I am now on my own. Things are so difficult; I have to take odd jobs in the village so as to buy necessities. The baby needs milk every 2-3 hours, and I can hardly sleep at night because he cries so much.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Mercy</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>&nbsp;We are very sorry for you my friend. Will you be able join form one next year?</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Jennifer</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>&nbsp;No I will not be able to because there is nobody to pay my fees now or even look after my baby. All my dreams of becoming a fashion designer. Please don&rsquo;t make the same mistake I made, concentrate on your goals and avoid situations where you can be forced to have sex against your will.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"69\">\n<p>Jane</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"592\">\n<p>&nbsp;It&rsquo;s getting late and we have to leave now, we&rsquo;ll come back to visit you.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz II/~/~Yes||/~Summary/~<p>As you have seen, getting pregnant can change your life dramatically especially if you did not plan for it. Therefore, it is important to abstain from having sex. So be responsible and make the healthy choice to abstain always. It can definitely make all the difference!!!</p>/~Yes||/~Myths and facts about Pregnancy/~<p>From the previous story we about Mercy and her friends to discuss the topic of pregnancy. If you recall, Jennifer became pregnant the first time she ever had sex. It changed her life for good. Jane also suspected that she might be pregnant because she had missed her period. We later learned that missing your period doesn&rsquo;t necessarily mean you are pregnant. Now let&rsquo;s play a game that will help us take a closer look at some of the other myths and facts related to pregnancy.</p>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz III/~/~Yes","","","","",""),
("24","6","Appreciating Me - Self Esteem","","img14.jpg","||/~Objective/~<p>By the end of this session you should be able to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Understand the meaning and importance of self-esteem.</li>\n<li>Assess your own personal worth.</li>\n<li>Consider ways of improving self-esteem.</li>\n<li>Address some of the things that negatively affect their esteem including puberty changes.</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~Introduction/~<p>We all unconsciously evaluate and have self-talk. If we have things that we appreciate about ourselves and we think more often about them we end up having a high esteem. But if there are things that we do not like about ourselves and we take time and think often about them, this lowers our self-esteem.</p>\n<p>We are talking about the value we place on ourselves.</p>/~Yes||/~What is self esteem?/~<p>We all unconsciously assign ourselves some value. This is what is called SELF ESTEEM. The core perception and beliefs we have of ourselves.</p>\n<p>If someone was to offer you money but throws it down and step on it?</p>\n<p>Does it change its value? Would you still take it?</p>\n<p>Money gets value based on the government and bank that back up and guarantees the value of the money. The paper is just a paper without the accompanying value guaranteed by the government that issues it. It follows then that the value is not changed even when it is stepped on. In the same way, one&rsquo;s value remains and is retained despite the circumstances they have gone through. We are created with that value. Whether we realize it or not, we have that inborn value. Self esteem calls us to recognize and appreciate that value and seek to be conscious about it.</p>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz I/~/~Yes||/~Esteem Influencers/~<p>High Esteem influencers</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Nice dress</li>\n<li>Good looking hair</li>\n<li>Positive comments from people</li>\n<li>Passing exams</li>\n<li>Talents we have</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Low Esteem influencers</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Negative comments from others</li>\n<li>Poor evaluation of dressing</li>\n<li>Inability to match our own expectations</li>\n<li>When we are unprepared to handle monthly periods</li>\n<li>Comparing ourselves with others</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Joan at School</h4>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color: #ccffff;\">One day Joan went to school early in the morning as usual.</span></em></p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color: #ccffff;\">She had always been prepared to deal with her periods in case it happened suddenly. On this particular day it happened and when she went to her bag she discovered that while organizing back her bag after washing over the weekend, she had forgotten to put back her Always pads.</span></em></p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color: #ccffff;\">She knew that other students were fond of laughing at girls when this would happen but she decided to calm down and not panic. She knew she was a special person and that this incident was another one reminding her that she was healthy and growing in life and so there was not point of being too embarrassed to handle the issue.</span></em></p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color: #ccffff;\">She waved at Mary who came over and she whispered what was going on. Mary went and got her Always pads and together the two girls went to the toilet and cleaned up. Joan knew her value does not change with events.</span></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The benefits of self-esteem are;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Great confidence</li>\n<li>Ability to engage people including those of high status in the community</li>\n<li>Ability to deal with risky situations</li>\n<li>Ability to take criticisms positively</li>\n<li>Ability to pursue ones goals and dreams to the end</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you have low self esteem consider the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Accept that the past incidents are past and the future has a lot to offer.</li>\n<li>Note that there are times we have unrealistic expectations because of external pressure.</li>\n<li>Look at the positive aspects of your life and constantly think about them and where appropriate talk to someone about them.</li>\n<li>There are some things we can do to avoid situations that may threaten our esteem, such as being prepared with the right items to handle monthly periods</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~Self-esteem Influencers/~<p><span style=\"background-color: #ccffff;\"><em>Natali is a class 7 girl who, until recently, has been a jovial and pleasant person. In the last few months she has become very quiet. It is being said that she is the biggest girl in school and there has been some cases where some people have made jokes about it. She seems to be wearing oversize sweaters possibly to hide her breasts which some girls say she looks like a mother.</em></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz II/~<p><span style=\"background-color: #ccffff;\"><em>Natali is a class 7 girl who, until recently, has been a jovial and pleasant person. In the last few months she has become very quiet. It is being said that she is the biggest girl in school and there has been some cases where some people have made jokes about it. She seems to be wearing oversize sweaters possibly to hide her breasts which some girls say she looks like a mother.</em></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz III/~<p><span style=\"background-color: #ccffff;\"><em>Natali is a class 7 girl who, until recently, has been a jovial and pleasant person. In the last few months she has become very quiet. It is being said that she is the biggest girl in school and there has been some cases where some people have made jokes about it. She seems to be wearing oversize sweaters possibly to hide her breasts which some girls say she looks like a mother.</em></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes","","","","",""),
("25","7","Appreciating Others - Interpersonal Relationships","","img15.jpg","||/~Objectives/~<p>By the end of this session you should be able to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Appreciate interpersonal relationships.</li>\n<li>Appreciate the individual&rsquo;s role in interpersonal relationships.</li>\n<li>Develop critical approaches to empathize with others.</li>\n<li>Develop approaches of dealing with pressure from peers.</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~Introduction/~<p>We all live with others and no matter how hard one tries; it is inevitable to interact with people.</p>\n<p>It becomes important to learn how to make the best of the relationships with people for mutual benefits.</p>/~Yes||/~Inter-personal relationships/~<ol>\n<li>There are many situations that cause us to find out about each other even when we are not engaging verbally.</li>\n<li>Human beings always look for a way of interacting with one another especially when there are some interests that they are pursuing.</li>\n<li>There was a moment of one-on-one. We have to deliberately nurture relationships and this requires building of trust. The more we build trust the more we are open to share about our lives</li>\n<li>Those who are close to us know more about us than those at a distance.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Let&rsquo;s look at the Relationship&nbsp;Matrix.</p>\n<p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~Types of inter-personal relationships/~<p>Relationships can be described in different ways one of them being the following:</p>\n<p><strong>Close</strong>: Relationships with those people we can share anything with and we trust.</p>\n<p><strong>Distant</strong>: Relationships with those people we hardly talk with and we know little about.</p>\n<p><strong>Short-term</strong>: Relationships with people we are meeting briefly and may never meet again.</p>\n<p><strong>Long-term</strong>: Relationships with people who we have to live with sometimes because of where we come from or family connections.</p>/~Yes||/~For Individual Reflection (Exercise)/~<p>Draw the relationship matrix as shown earlier. Write the names of people in your life in the boxes you feel is appropriate as per the description give above.</p>\n<p><strong>Box 1</strong>. Write the names of the people, possibly family members who you are close to.</p>\n<p><strong>Box 2</strong>. Write the names of people, possibly family members who you have nothing or very little to do with.</p>\n<p><strong>Box 3</strong>. Write the names of people you have met briefly but you shared very personally.</p>\n<p><strong>Box 4</strong>. Write the names of people you have met briefly and that ended there and have no close interactions.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"402\" /></p>/~Yes||/~Feeling for Others - Empathy/~<p>People around us go through different and sometimes difficult circumstances. This is sometimes caused by the body changes they are going through and are not prepared to handle them. We need to be able to put ourselves in their situations, feel with them and support them appropriately. In doing this, we feel for them. In other words we are showing empathy.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h4>Jane&rsquo;s Story</h4>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ccffff;\"><em>One time Jane was seated in school when she suddenly felt some wetness in her clothes. When she stood up she saw some spots of blood on her seat and was shocked because she did not know what was going on.</em></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ccffff;\"><em>To her surprise, Anne came and wrapped her sweater round her and in a whisper told her not to worry about anything; she was going to help her. The two girls went out together at break time and to Jane&rsquo;s surprise, Anne showed her how to use sanitary pads she had carried in her bag and from that day Jane understood that it is normal and she needs to be prepared to handle this on a monthly basis.</em></span></p>\n<h4>Relationship Pressures</h4>\n<p><em>Step 1</em></p>\n<p>Reflect on the following comments</p>\n<ul>\n<li>&ldquo;She made me do it!!</li>\n<li>&ldquo;Everyone is doing it!!</li>\n<li>&ldquo;I need to have what she has!!</li>\n<li>&ldquo;It is the &lsquo;in thing&rsquo; nowadays!!</li>\n<li>&ldquo;If I do not do it, they will not be happy with me!!</li>\n<li>&ldquo;I will lose my friends forever if I don&rsquo;t!!</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>Step 2</em></p>\n<p>Rank the the statements from the most commonly used to the least commonly used according to what you have heard or experienced.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~Conclusion/~<p>Relationship pressure commonly known as peer pressure affects everyone, sometimes positively but at other times negatively. Positive pressure is that which has desirable long term results in our lives while as negative is what leaves us with guilt in the near or long-term future.</p>\n<p>We need to watch out on those that may easily lead us astray because of how close we have brought them into our lives.</p>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz/~/~Yes","","","","",""),
("26","8","Goal Setting (My future/Academics/ Studies/Talents)","","img12.jpg","||/~Objectives/~<p>By the end of this session you should be able to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Appreciate role of goal setting in your life.</li>\n<li>Develop focus by planning for your future.</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~Introduction/~<p>Many of the people who have succeeded in life have done so largely because they had an idea of what they wanted in life. Have you ever met someone who started on a journey without an idea of where they were going and how they would know when they got there?</p>/~Yes||/~My Role in My Future/~<p>In order for you to take charge of your planned future, you need to do the following:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>You have to <strong>name it</strong> before you can have it. We need not be afraid to believe the things that we long for (goals).</li>\n<li>The desires that are in us cause us to move a step at a time towards making them a reality.</li>\n<li>T he future is open to us to make it what we would want it to be.</li>\n<li>Our education is a major pillar in bringing about the desired goals.</li>\n</ol>/~Yes||/~Visualizing My Future/~<p>In order to create concrete plans towards one&rsquo;s future one has to be able to visualize the desired future. As a guide you one can use key pillars and write down the desired future against the pillar. Examples of pillars to consider are:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Your friends</li>\n<li>Your Education</li>\n<li>Your Health</li>\n<li>Where you want to live</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Activity</strong>: Write down what your see (desire to see) against each pillar in 10 years time.</p>\n<p>(<em>It is important for the learner to spend at least 10 minutes to visualize and write down on a piece of paper what they desire to see under each of those pillars. These shall be required for later exercises</em>)</p>/~Yes||/~Addressing the Barriers to My Future/~<p>In addressing the barriers please write down what, in your opinion, can stop you from reaching your desired future. For each barrier identify look for how you can tackle the barrier so that you can remain focused on your future as shown below.</p>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"273\">\n<p>What can stop me reaching my future?</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"342\">\n<p>What can I do to ensure it does not stop my plans</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"273\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"342\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"273\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"342\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"273\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"342\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"273\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n<td width=\"342\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz/~/~Yes","","","","",""),
("27","9","Financial Planning Basics in financial planning","","img28.jpg","||/~Objectives/~<p>Budgeting &ndash; making a personal budget</p>\n<p>The objectives of this unit are to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>To increase your understanding of financial term &ldquo;Budget&rdquo;</li>\n<li>To enhance your ability to link cash flow to a budget.</li>\n<li>Create a platform where you practice making financial calculations.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~What exactly is a Budget?/~<p>BUDGET is a summary of estimated income and how it will be spent over time. A budget is a plan that divides the money you have into how you are going to spend it and save it in a certain amount of time. Expenses and income are two of the main parts.</p>\n<p>To make a budget, you need to know how much money you have coming in and how you want to spend it in a certain period of time. Making a budget is organizing how you spend your money.</p>/~Yes||/~Steps for making a Budget /~<ul>\n<li>Review your financial goals &ndash; Think about your financial goals, both in the long-term and short-term.</li>\n<li>Estimate Amount of Income by source &ndash; Figure out how much money you make from each of the different ways you make money.</li>\n<li>List all Expenses an amount needed for each one &ndash; figure out the different things that you spend money on and how much you spend on each.</li>\n<li>Make sure your expenses are not more than your income &ndash; compare your total income with your total expenses to make sure that you&rsquo;re not going to spend more that you make.</li>\n<li>Decide how much you will save &ndash; plan on saving money for your different goals. Make it a reasonable amount based on your income and expenses.</li>\n<li>Review and change as needed &ndash; look over your budget every so often and add things or take them away to reflect any changes in your life</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~How to create a Budget/~<p><strong>Income</strong>: define some source of income</p>\n<p><strong>Expenditures</strong>: personal; education; family etc</p>\n<p><strong>Estimates</strong> &ndash; (guess) your expenses for each category for each week.</p>\n<p>Compare Income and Expenditures &ndash; subtract the total spending for each week from total expected income for each week</p>\n<h4>Order of the Steps to Create a Budget</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Review your financial goals.</li>\n<li>Estimate Amount of Income by source</li>\n<li>List all expenses and amount needed for each one</li>\n<li>Make sure your expenses are not more than your income</li>\n<li>Decide how much you will save</li>\n<li>Review and change as needed.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>N B: Different People Have Different Budgets; distinguish between Needs and Wants.</p>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz/~/~Yes","","","","",""),
("28","10","Managing Risky Situations - Negotiation Skills Risky Situations Review","","img29.jpg","||/~Situations/~<ol>\n<li><strong>Risky situation within your environment</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Drugs and alcohol can impair your judgment and prevent you from making healthy choices.</p>\n<p>Using drugs and alcohol can make you engage in sex when you are not prepared, it can make you engage in risky sexual behavior such as having sex with strangers, or sometimes even engaging in violent sexual activity.</p>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li><strong>Receiving gifts/money</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Accepting gifts or money may put you at higher risks for STIs including HIV infection because people may give you gifts expecting sex in return. You may not be in a position to say no to sexual advances once you have accepted the money/gift. The healthy choice to make is not to accept anything from strangers or from people whose intention you do not know. Before you accept a gift from anyone, find out any intentions behind the money/gift and if you will be required to give sexual favors in return.</p>\n<ol start=\"3\">\n<li><strong>Cross-generational friendships (Being in a relationship with somebody who is older than you)</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you have a friendship with a person who is much older, your ability to negotiate for abstinence may be compromised. Often older persons can buy you gifts or money and will expect sexual favors in return. Having a friend of your age makes it easier for you, you share the same interest and it&rsquo;s easier to discuss about sex matters and abstinence.</p>\n<p>Older persons are also more likely to have other sexual partners or have an STI or HIV, and can put your health in danger. Also, they probably can argue better and may try convincing you to do something you are not really up to.(E.G. a shopkeeper or a security guard&hellip;etc)</p>\n<ol start=\"4\">\n<li><strong>Casual sex</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Having sex with someone you have just met can be very risky. This is because you don&rsquo;t know that person&rsquo;s sexual history, including if he/she has a sexually transmitted infection or not. You cannot tell that someone is healthy just by looking at them.</p>\n<ol start=\"5\">\n<li><strong>Isolated/hidden places</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>It is important to avoid walking alone in an isolated place where somebody could force you to do something against your will, for example having sex. Such places are for example, walking alone at night or idling alone in the market; being alone in a room with a male. In such situations, you should shout for help, run away and tell someone you trust about what has happened.</p>/~Yes||/~Resisting Peer Pressure/~<h3>Introduction</h3>\n<p>Friends can sometimes put pressure or force on one another forcing an individual to do things that they may not necessarily want to do. Peer pressure may be positive, for example, when peers exert pressure on each other to study. Most of the times peer pressure is negative, for example peers forcing others to have sex. You need to deal with negative peer pressure assertively.</p>\n<h3>Objectives</h3>\n<p>By the end of this session you should be able to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Discuss the peer pressure you experience and its impact.</li>\n<li>Practice assertiveness and negotiation skills in dealing with peer pressure.</li>\n<li>Make a personal plan of action towards dealing with negative peer pressure more effectively.</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~What is Peer Pressure?/~<p>Peer pressure is the real or imagined force or coercion one experiences from his or her peers to act or behave in a certain way.</p>/~Yes||/~Methods of resisting peer pressure/~<p>Use of assertiveness is a very helpful way of dealing with peer pressure. The following are ways of being assertive</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Speak in a clear voice.</li>\n<li>Be convinced that you are doing the right thing.</li>\n<li>Do not fidget with your fingers while talking or &lsquo;writing&rsquo; with your toes.</li>\n<li>Look at the other person(s) straight in the eyes.</li>\n<li>Listen attentively as well as allow the other person to talk.</li>\n<li>Use polite but firm words.</li>\n<li>In case the other person tries to get you off the point, keep to the topic of discussion.</li>\n<li>Use and repeat the word &ldquo;NO&rdquo; often</li>\n<li>Send a strong nonverbal &ldquo;no&rdquo; with your body language, (for example, use hand and body gestures to emphasize the point)</li>\n<li>Project a strong serious-like tone of voice.</li>\n<li>Show you are in control.</li>\n<li>Look directly at the person&rsquo;s face and eyes. Don&rsquo;t put your head down.</li>\n<li>Stand straight and tall. Don&rsquo;t fumble with things.</li>\n<li>Use a serious facial expression</li>\n<li>Don&rsquo;t send mixed signals (such as smiling while you are saying &ldquo;no&rdquo;)</li>\n<li>Communicate your feelings in ways like the following:\n<ol>\n<li>I feel like you don&rsquo;t really care about me when you pressure me like this.</li>\n<li>If you can&rsquo;t respect my feelings, then I&rsquo;m prepared to end this relationship.</li>\n<li>Our future goals and dreams are more important than a moment of pleasure.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~Making my Point Consider the following situations/~/~Yes||/~Quick quiz/~/~Yes","","","","",""),
("29","11","Gender Based Violence (GBV) and Conflict","","img31.jpg","||/~Session Goals/~<ul>\n<li>To explore and recognize concepts and concerns related to GBV</li>\n<li>To raise awareness of the impact of violent conflict on GBV</li>\n<li>To enhance capacities to develop prevention, protection and response strategies of GBV in the context of violent conflict</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Objectives</h4>\n<p>By the end of this session you would be able to increase knowledge, awareness and skills in:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Understanding GBV: defining GBV, understanding the types, causes and effects of GBV, exploring frameworks</li>\n<li>Protecting from and responding to GBV: identifying risks and threats in conflict settings, practicing how to respond to GBV</li>\n<li>Preventing GBV: identifying prevention strategies such as engaging men and boys and community mobilization.</li>\n<li>Understand the intricacies of GBV, and recognize how to better prevent, protect and respond to GBV.</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~Definitions of Conflict/~<p><strong>Conflict </strong>is defined as a clash between individuals arising out of a difference in thought process, attitudes, understanding, interests, requirements and even sometimes perceptions. A <strong>conflict</strong> results in heated arguments, physical abuses and definitely loss of peace and harmony.</p>/~Yes||/~Forms/types of Conflict/~<h4>Levels of conflict</h4>\n<ol>\n<ol>\n<li>Interpersonal: Interpersonal conflicts occur between two or more people.</li>\n<li>Intra-group: Intra-group conflicts occur between people within the same group.</li>\n<li>Inter-group: Inter-group conflicts occur between groups (communities, organizations, cultures, and nations).</li>\n</ol>\n</ol>\n<h4>Conflict Analysis</h4>\n<ol>\n<ol>\n<li>Conflict tree (roots &ndash; causes, trunk &ndash; core problem and branches &ndash; effects)</li>\n<li>Conflict triangle (attitude, behavior and contradiction)&nbsp;</li>\n</ol>\n</ol>\n<h4>Impact of conflict</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Direct impact: Excess mortality, (increased) sexual and gender based violence, separation of families, disease, displacement, migration, widowhood, loss of assets and income.</li>\n<li>Indirect impact: Increased HIV/AIDS infections, reduced access to health care, negative impact on reproductive health, female-headed households, poverty, trauma, depression, destruction of social networks, increased economic and political participation.</li>\n</ol>/~Yes||/~Effective Communication Skills for Peace Building/~<p><strong>Speaking</strong>: A speaker communicates both verbally, with words, and nonverbally, with eye contact, body movements and facial expressions.</p>\n<p><strong>Listening</strong>: A listener communicates that he or she has heard the speaker&rsquo;s message both through paraphrasing and asking questions with words and nonverbally, with eye contact, body movements and facial expressions.</p>/~Yes||/~Defining and understanding GBV/~<h4>Objective</h4>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<li>To help participants define and understand gender-based violence and related key concepts.</li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~Perpetrators vs. Survivors/~<h4>Potential perpetrators</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Intimate partners (husbands, boyfriends)</li>\n<li>Influential community members (teachers, leaders, politicians)</li>\n<li>Security forces, soldiers, peacekeepers</li>\n<li>Humanitarian aid workers (international, national, refugee staff)</li>\n<li>Strangers</li>\n<li>Members of the community</li>\n<li>Relatives (brothers, uncles, parents, aunts, sisters, etc.)</li>\n<li>Anyone who is in a position of power</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Survivors</h4>\n<p>A <strong>victim </strong>is defined by the harm that has come to them; a <strong>survivor </strong>is defined by their life afterwards. A <strong>victim</strong> has been destroyed and mistreated; a <strong>survivor</strong> has continued to live and prosper despite having been victimized.</p>/~Yes||/~Checking on Existing Knowledge of GBV/~<h4>GBV defining concepts</h4>\n<p>Let&rsquo;s now explore each of the core concepts which will lead us to a working definition of gender-based violence.</p>\n<p><strong>GBV</strong>: comprises the use of force &ndash;including threats, abuse, and coercion (not only physical). Gender-based violence is violence involving men and women, in which the female is usually the victim; and which is derived from unequal power relationships between men and women. Violence is directed specifically against a woman because she is a woman, or affects women disproportionately. It includes, but is not limited to, physical, sexual, and psychological harm&hellip;</p>\n<p>It includes that violence which is perpetuated or condoned by the state. &ndash;United Nations Population</p>/~Yes||/~The GBV Tree/~<p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" alt=\"\" width=\"481\" height=\"294\" /></p>\n<h4>Objectives</h4>\n<p>By the end of this subsection you will be able:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>to understand the different forms of GBV</li>\n<li>To increase knowledge of the root causes of GBV</li>\n<li>To increase awareness of potential contributing factors to GBV, specifically in conflict settings</li>\n<li>To understand the potential consequences and effects of GBV</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" alt=\"\" width=\"575\" height=\"430\" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" alt=\"\" width=\"503\" height=\"616\" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~Identifying and reducing risks of GBV in conflict/~<p>Forms of GBV</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sexual</li>\n<li>Physical</li>\n<li>Emotional/ Mental</li>\n<li>Social/Economic</li>\n<li>Harmful Traditional Practices</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~Examples of GBV/~<p><strong>Rape/Attempted Rape</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Sexual Abuse, </strong></p>\n<p><strong>Sexual Exploitation, </strong></p>\n<p><strong>Forced Early Marriage</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Domestic Violence</strong>: Intimate Partner or Other Family Members,</p>\n<p><strong>Trafficking for Sex or Labor, Female Genital Cutting (FGC), </strong></p>\n<p><strong>Other Gender-based Violence</strong>: This includes physical, mental, or social abuse that is directed against a person because of his or her gender role in a society or culture.</p>\n<p>Examples include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A girl is not allowed to go to school because of gender role expectations in the family (housekeeping, cooking, care of children, etc.);</li>\n<li>A girl or woman is required to marry against her will according to local custom; or&nbsp;</li>\n<li>A woman or girl is prevented from freely walking around in her own community because of cultural practices that require women to be accompanied by a male when in public.</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~Reporting GBV/~<p>There is a serious problem of underreporting regarding incidents of GBV.</p>\n<p>Reasons: Self-blame, stigma and rejection of their family or community, fear of reprisals, mistrust of authorities. You may assume that any available data, in any setting, on GBV from governments, NGOs, health workers or other sources represents only a very small proportion of the actual number of incidents.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~Engaging men and boys in GBV prevention/~<ul>\n<li>To deepen understanding of the importance of engaging men and boys in challenging GBV</li>\n<li>To help participants identify possibilities to engaging men and boys in their projects</li>\n<li>Harmful gender norms and gender inequality are root causes of GBV, and they affect how men interact with women.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Engaging men in addressing harmful norms is important to prevent GBV and promote equality.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Deficit programming: men are seen as obstacles or the problems</li>\n<li>Asset-based programming: men do care about their partners, families, and can be allies for change; their needs must be addressed as well</li>\n<li>In conflict, social norms change or are hard to fulfill (be providers and protectors). This negatively affects relationships between men and women.</li>\n</ul>/~Yes||/~Quick quiz/~/~Yes","","","","",""),
("31","1","Introduction","","img10.jpg","||/~What is Lasting Impressions?/~<p>Lasting Impressions is a programme that helps the adolescents to understand the change that occur in them during this stage and how to cope with the challenges associated with these changes.</p>\n<p>It aims to help teenagers practice healthy norms that are geared to positive and lasting impressions in their lives.</p>/~Yes||/~Programme Coverage and requirements/~<p>This programme covers 12 topics that the learner needs to review. The sessions covered are:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Introduction</li>\n<li>Self Awareness</li>\n<li>Body Changes at Puberty</li>\n<li>Sexuality</li>\n<li>Teen Pregnancy and Sexually Transmitted Infections</li>\n<li>Appreciating Me &ndash; Self Esteem</li>\n<li>Appreciating others &ndash; Interpersonal Relationships</li>\n<li>Goal Setting (My future/Academics/Studies/Talents)</li>\n<li>Financial planning basics</li>\n<li>Managing Risky situations &ndash; Negotiation Skills; Risky situation Review</li>\n<li>Gender Based Violence and Conflict</li>\n<li>Review Questions and Answers</li>\n</ol>\n<p>At the end of each session there will be review questions with multiple choice answers.</p>\n<p>To successfully complete the programme, you are required to complete reviewing all the 12 sessions and attempt all questions.</p>/~Yes||/~Life Skills/~/~Yes||/~Definition/~<p><em>Life skills are abilities for adaptive and positive behavior that enables individuals to deal effectively with demands and challenges of day to day life.</em></p>\n<p>We all go through different stages in life.&nbsp; Different stages bring about different aspects of us and depending on how well we are prepared to handle the situations, we can either cope or struggle with them.&nbsp; The amazing thing is we can develop skills to handle various situations life brings our way.&nbsp; These skills are called life skills.&nbsp;</p>/~Yes||/~Quiz/~/~Yes","","","","","");



